      "body": "<h2>Language injection</h2>\n<p>Beyond Javaâ€™s <a href=\"https://openjdk.org/jeps/378\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><em>Text Blocks</em></a> feature covered in <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/50155171/642706\">this correct Answer</a>, your <a href=\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integrated_development_environment\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">IDE</a> may provide additional support for display and editing of multiline text in a language-savvy manner.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/IntelliJ_IDEA\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">IntelliJ</a> IDE provides for <em>language injections</em>. See <a href=\"https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/using-language-injections.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this article</a> and <a href=\"https://youtu.be/Au6NTrpTr_o?si=c6xHgboU-Zrdbylv\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">video by Helen Scott</a>. You can flag the embedded language by using either annotation or a comment.</p>\n<p>Language injection works well with Java text blocks.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>@Language (&quot;SQL&quot;) \nString sql = &quot;&quot;&quot;\n    SELECT *\n    FROM product_\n    ;\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;;\n</code></pre>\n<p>IntelliJ will colorize the embedded language. And you can open a dedicated editor section to provide for language-appropriate editing. See <a href=\"https://blog.jetbrains.com/idea/2020/06/language-injections-in-intellij-idea/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this article</a>.</p>\n<p>Language injection works for SQL, JSON, RegExp, and more.</p>\n<p>Other IDEs may provide a similar feature.</p>\n"
    },
