      "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body": "<h2><em>Text Blocks</em></h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/378\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><em>JEP 378: Text Blocks</em></a> covers this functionality. This feature became a standard part of <a href=\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_version_history#Java_15\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Java 15</a> and later.</p>\n<p>It first appeared as <a href=\"https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/355\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><em>JEP 355: Text Blocks (Preview)</em></a> in JDK 13 and <a href=\"https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/368\" rel=\"noreferrer\">JEP 368: Text Blocks (Second Preview)</a> in JDK 14 as <a href=\"https://openjdk.org/jeps/12\" rel=\"noreferrer\">preview feature</a>.</p>\n<p>The syntax allows writing something like:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>String s = &quot;&quot;&quot;\n        text\n        text\n        text\n        &quot;&quot;&quot;;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Previous to this JEP, in JDK 12, <a href=\"http://openjdk.java.net/jeps/326\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><em>JEP 326: Raw String Literals</em></a> aimed to implement a similar feature, but it was later withdrawn.</p>\n"
